00:51:45.010 --> 00:51:47.110
or game is your favorite?

00:51:47.110 --> 00:51:48.760
SAM WITWER: Sort of
the Erol Otus era.

00:51:48.760 --> 00:51:50.009
MICHAEL WITWER: Oh, Erol Otus.

00:51:50.009 --> 00:51:52.450
KYLE NEWMAN: Yeah,
we love his art.

00:51:52.450 --> 00:51:56.080
JON PETERSON: We just had him
with us at Games of Berkeley.

00:51:56.080 --> 00:51:57.730
MICHAEL WITWER: Just
a couple days ago.

00:51:57.730 --> 00:51:58.830
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:51:58.830 --> 00:51:59.831
That's about circa 1980.

00:51:59.831 --> 00:52:01.538
SAM WITWER: Do you
know who Erol Otus is?

00:52:01.538 --> 00:52:03.240
Do you know the art
we're talking about?

00:52:03.240 --> 00:52:08.290
OK, so his art was
extremely colorful.

00:52:08.290 --> 00:52:10.960
Like it looked like
something out of a--

00:52:10.960 --> 00:52:13.690
KYLE NEWMAN: It was exciting
new colors and shapes

00:52:13.690 --> 00:52:15.060
that weren't as traditional.

00:52:15.060 --> 00:52:19.467
I think he's like the El
Greco of "D&amp;D" fantasy art.

00:52:19.467 --> 00:52:20.300
He's pretty awesome.

00:52:20.300 --> 00:52:23.050
MICHAEL WITWER: You can see his
shot from "Deities &amp; Demigods."

00:52:23.050 --> 00:52:24.360
The first printing.

00:52:24.360 --> 00:52:25.860
If anyone knows the
Moldvay box set,

00:52:25.860 --> 00:52:27.234
he was the one
that did the cover

00:52:27.234 --> 00:52:28.810
of this particular iconic piece.

00:52:28.810 --> 00:52:31.240
No one does art like him.

00:52:31.240 --> 00:52:32.059
He was unique.

00:52:32.059 --> 00:52:33.600
KYLE NEWMAN: They
weren't putting him

00:52:33.600 --> 00:52:35.740
in a box saying you have
to draw this or do that.

00:52:35.740 --> 00:52:37.150
He was unhinged.

00:52:37.150 --> 00:52:38.530
They just let him be him.

00:52:38.530 --> 00:52:41.071
I think that's what's beautiful
about "Dungeons and Dragons,"

00:52:41.071 --> 00:52:42.520
it's like a catch-all.

00:52:42.520 --> 00:52:44.920
It's not like "Lord of the
Rings" where it has one feel.

00:52:44.920 --> 00:52:47.027
It's a quirky catch-all
where anything goes.

00:52:47.027 --> 00:52:48.610
I think that speaks
to the game, which

00:52:48.610 --> 00:52:50.710
is you bring your
imagination, your group

00:52:50.710 --> 00:52:53.590
can do it any way you
want at any rating system,

00:52:53.590 --> 00:52:56.380
and you can take even
our structured product

00:52:56.380 --> 00:52:58.900
and go off on a tangent
and make it your own.

00:52:58.900 --> 00:52:59.980
That's the beauty of it.

00:52:59.980 --> 00:53:02.271
SAM WITWER: People like Erol
Otus definitely encouraged

00:53:02.271 --> 00:53:05.530
that, because there was a sort
